<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH COMMENT IRRITATES TAIWAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush's assertion Thursday that Taiwan supports an extension of trade 
benefits for China embarrassed Taiwan's Nationalist government, which issued a 
quick denial. 
</P>
<P>
At his press conference, Bush twice said that in the last few weeks, Taiwan has 
been among the Asian governments urging the Administration to continue China's 
most-favored-nation trading status. 
</P>
<P>
"Korea, Japan, Thailand, Singapore, even Taiwan made clear that MFN should be 
retained," Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
Not so, said Taiwan's government. 
</P>
<P>
Within a few hours, Ding Mou-shih, the head of Taiwan's unofficial embassy 
here, called a press conference to say that he and his government had not in 
any way endorsed the trade benefits for the Communist regime in Beijing. 
</P>
