<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOESKY TELLS OF ILLEGAL TIPS FROM MILKEN; 
</P>
<P>
WALL STREET: THE FORMER INSIDE TRADER ALSO SAYS HE BROKE FEDERAL LAW BY PAYING 
FELLOW PRISON INMATES TO DO HIS LAUNDRY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOT J. PALTROW, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ivan F. Boesky gave the first public evidence Thursday that former Drexel 
Burnham Lambert junk bond chief Michael Milken had illegally fed him inside 
information about stocks. 
</P>
<P>
Asked by a defense lawyer in the trial of John A. Mulheren Jr. to name all of 
the people who had given him illegal inside tips, Boesky said "Mr. Milken comes 
to mind." 
</P>
<P>
But Boesky, formerly one of Wall Street's leading speculators in takeover 
stocks, said he didn't know how much money he had made from the information 
Milken had passed to him. "I haven't made a compilation, sir," Boesky said. 
</P>
<P>
Milken pleaded guilty to six felony counts last month and is awaiting 
sentencing. Several of the counts related to transactions with Boesky. None of 
them, however, had to do with inside trading, a point which Milken's lawyers 
and press spokesman strongly emphasized at the time. Milken's spokesman has 
long denied that Milken leaked inside information or traded on it himself, 
although he was accused of it in an indictment that has since been dropped. 
</P>
<P>
Ken Lerer, Milken's spokesman, said Thursday that he wouldn't comment on 
Boesky's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
Boesky, 53, was excused Thursday after testifying for two and a half days as 
the main prosecution witness in Mulheren's trial. Like Boesky, Mulheren was a 
stock arbitrager. Mulheren faces federal criminal charges of securities fraud 
and conspiracy related to his business dealings with Boesky. 
</P>
<P>
Testimony about Milken was elicited by Mulheren's lawyer, Thomas Puccio, who 
attempted to demolish Boesky's credibility by showing that he had lied 
repeatedly under oath and engaged in extensive illegal activities. Boesky said 
Milken was the only individual he remembered leaking him inside information 
besides the two he had already named, former investment bankers Dennis Levine 
and Martin A. Siegel. 
</P>
<P>
Throughout the grueling cross-examination, however, Boesky claimed that he 
couldn't remember names, details or specific amounts of money. He said he 
couldn't recall which companies Milken had leaked information about. 
</P>
<P>
Boesky's nearly total inability to recall amounts of money at times appeared to 
stymie Puccio. The defense lawyer is attempting to show that Boesky has 
considerable personal wealth left despite the $100 million in penalties Boesky 
paid when he pleaded guilty to a single felony count. The defense theory is 
that Boesky's agreement with the government to turn in others enabled him to 
keep a big part of his wealth. 
</P>
<P>
Boesky claimed that the huge volume of stock trading he did -- up to 300 
million shares a year -- made it difficult for him to recall how much money he 
made on any deal. Asked if he had made $57 million in profit after receiving an 
inside tip about Getty Oil in the early 1980s, Boesky said he didn't remember. 
</P>
<P>
"Isn't it true that if you made in the neighborhood of $57 million on a certain 
stock it would stick out in your mind?" Puccio asked. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it would necessarily stick out in my memory," Boesky said. 
</P>
<P>
Boesky also said he couldn't recall whether he had transferred assets to his 
wife and children when the government began investigating him in 1986 to reduce 
the amount of money the government could seize from him. "I do not recall my 
financial activities in 1986," he said. 
</P>
<P>
But under close questioning, Boesky did recall that he was able to deduct from 
his 1986 taxes half of the $100-million penalty he paid. 
</P>
<P>
Puccio said outside the courtroom that one possible reason for Boesky's 
apparent severe memory problems is his concern about the many civil lawsuits he 
faces. Boesky has testified that he faces more than $1 billion in civil claims 
filed by people and companies that contend they were defrauded by his illegal 
activities. Anything Boesky said on the witness stand in the Mulheren trial 
could be used against him in the civil lawsuits. A lawyer for Boesky failed to 
return a telephone call asking for comment Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Boesky also said he had broken federal law during the 19 months he had spent as 
an inmate at the minimum-security federal prison camp in Lompoc by paying 
fellow inmates to do his laundry. A spokesman for the federal Bureau of Prisons 
said in a phone interview that hiring fellow inmates would have violated prison 
rules, although the spokesman said he wasn't certain what law it might have 
violated. 
</P>
<P>
Puccio also asked Boesky if he had bribed officials at the prison, including 
one of the wardens. Boesky strongly denied it. 
</P>
<P>
While answering questions from reporters later, Puccio refused to say if he had 
any evidence that Boesky had committed bribery. The prisons spokesman said: "We 
have no knowledge of any bribes occurring in this facility with any staff 
member." 
</P>
<P>
In court, Puccio had intimated that when Boesky was sentenced in 1987, he had 
given false information to the sentencing judge that the $100-million penalty 
would leave him nearly bankrupt. Puccio refused to say afterwards if he plans 
to introduce evidence later in the trial showing that Boesky had lied on that 
point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
