<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP MUSIC REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
SOUND MINUS VISION; 
</P>
<P>
CONCERT: DAVID BOWIE'S IMMINENT RETIREMENT OF HIS CLASSICS ON HIS 'SOUND + 
VISION' TOUR HAS ALREADY LEFT THEM LIFELESS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD CROMELIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's hard to see where you're going when you're looking back. 
</P>
<P>
David Bowie's "Sound + Vision" tour offers a peculiar premise for a show by a 
big rock star: Nothing but old songs, and on top of that it's their final spin. 
After the tour, Bowie will no longer get lost in space as Major Tom, nor 
celebrate the sci-fi rock star Ziggy Stardust, nor encourage his fans to face 
their ch-ch-ch-changes. 
</P>
<P>
Is this a gimmick to drum up interest in the tour? A daring gesture to put his 
future artistry on the line (the idea is that shelving his old favorites will 
force Bowie to rely on his new work)? Or is it a lazy way to stage an 
undemanding concert, avoiding the challenge of combining his past with his 
present? 
</P>
<P>
Whatever the slippery star's true motivation, the result on stage at the Los 
Angeles Sports Arena on Wednesday night was erratic at best: occasionally 
inspired, mostly flat. 
</P>
<P>
What could be wrong with a good, uncomplicated wallow in the canon of this rock 
titan? 
</P>
<P>
Well, the lesson is that a totally retrospective show, even one loaded with 
major material and built-in drama, needs the balance and forward movement that 
even some token new material would provide. Nobody went to the Stones shows to 
hear stuff from "Steel Wheels," but scattered in the nostalgia, those songs at 
least offered a convincing illusion of vitality. 
</P>
<P>
Bowie's performance suggested that rather than bringing a special poignancy and 
edge to his classics, their imminent retirement has already left them lifeless. 
The knowledge that they're on their last legs deflates them instead of 
enhancing them, and they didn't even generate much of the valedictory 
sentimentality that should have been the cheapest emotion at their command. 
</P>
<P>
Definitive, committed execution would have helped, but Bowie's band -- 
especially the overactive guitarist Adrian Belew -- specializes in mowing down 
nuance, and the singer's interest level seemed to fluctuate radically. 
</P>
<P>
He put the most into two of his landmarks, "Life on Mars?" and "Ziggy 
Stardust," but he looked as ridiculous as he's said he feels in the Stonesy 
glitter-rock of "Rebel, Rebel." He offered selections for fans of most of his 
incarnations, with the emphasis on the post-"Ziggy" years. 
</P>
<P>
On a stage flanked by carved columns and decorated with medieval-looking 
statuary of beasts and angels, Bowie slipped in and out of a theatrical mode. 
Most of the songs were enhanced by gigantic, ghostlike images projected on a 
transparent screen: an effective integration of the star in the flesh with the 
star's assorted public images and private emanations. 
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Bowie's casual manner was doubly refreshing after his last 
tour's distancing stagecraft. He seemed even looser than he did at last year's 
surprise Roxy show with his stripped-down group Tin Machine. 
</P>
<P>
Often stationed on a stage extension that jutted into the audience, he smiled 
and joked, sometimes almost nervously. He opened the post-intermission segment 
by strolling out strumming with Belew while the house lights were still on, and 
at the encore he even teased the crowd by saying: "I know who killed Laura 
Palmer." 
</P>
<P>
If he can create the same kind of intimacy when he plays Dodger Stadium on 
Saturday, Bowie will be a real magician. But with this show, there's still no 
way he can avoid being a lame duck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, A refreshingly casual David Bowie concentrates on his past 
glories at the Los Angeles Sports Arena. MARSHA TRAEGER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
