<P>
2 INJURED AS PLANE FALLS SHORT OF RUNWAY AT FULLERTON AIRPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Piper 18 Super-Cub aircraft crashed just short of the runway at the Fullerton 
Municipal Airport today and hit a telephone pole, injuring the two men on 
board, a fire official said. 
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred at 10:47 a.m. in an open space in an industrial area near 
Artesia Avenue and just short of the runway. 
</P>
<P>
Names of the injured were not immediately known, and it was unclear how 
seriously injured they are. 
</P>
<P>
Arriving paramedics placed the men on back boards because of possible back 
injuries, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Fire Marshal Marc Martin said the men "managed to get out of the airplane under 
their own power. When the firefighters arrived, they were out of the plane." 
</P>
<P>
"There was no fire," Martin said. "There was some fuel which had spilled from 
the airplane. Both patients have injuries. (I) don't know the extent of their 
injuries." 
</P>
<P>
They were treated at the scene and transported to St. Jude Hospital in 
Fullerton. 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody on the ground was injured, and, as far as I know, there was no other 
damage on the ground," Martin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
